Aims of WHS Legislation

1. Protect the health, safety and wellbeing of persons at workplace.
2. Eliminate risks to health, safety and wellbeing of persons at work and the public.
3. Ensure employers and workers collaborate on issues affecting workplace health and safety.
4. Assist employers to achieve a healthy and safe workplace.

The Model Workplace Health 2011 was developed by Safe Work Australia with the aim of providing 
a nationally consistent WHS framework to secure the health and safety of workers across Australia.

The guidelines from the National Health and Medical Research Council (NHMRC) and the Australian Commission 
on Safety and Quality in Healthcare were published in 2019

Persons conducting a business or undertaking (PCBU)
 Must eliminate, if possible, or minimise risks so far as is reasonably practicable
 Must consult with workers about how safety is manage
 Must put in place procedures for hazard and incident reporting

Officers (for example, company directors)
 Must ensure PCBU is complying with WHS acts and regulations
 Must maintain understanding of business and WHS requirements

Designers, manufacturers and suppliers
 Must ensure their products are free of risks to health and safety.

Workers
 Must take reasonable care for themselves and others
 Must comply with WHS procedures
 Must wear PPE provided
 Must report any risks to safety they identify

